---
import PageLayout from '../layouts/PageLayout.astro';
---

<PageLayout title="About" description="About FlowHat Blog">
	<h1>About FlowHat Blog</h1>
	<p>
		FlowHat Blog is an independent publication about LLMs, AI agents, coding tools, and practical
		software workflows. The site exists for readers who want more than announcement summaries. The goal
		is to explain what changed, why it matters, and how a developer, builder, or technical operator might
		actually use the tool.
	</p>

	<h2>What the site covers</h2>
	<p>
		The current scope is intentionally narrow. FlowHat Blog focuses on models, agent products, coding
		agents, subagents, skill systems, multimodal workflows, developer tools, and the operational details
		around using them well.
	</p>
	<p>
		Typical topics include Claude Code, OpenAI Codex, ChatGPT agent features, Gemini, Gemma, Kimi,
		Qwen, Hugging Face, Superpowers, gstack, GSD, local model tooling, and adjacent infrastructure that
		changes how people build with AI systems.
	</p>

	<h2>Editorial approach</h2>
	<p>
		FlowHat Blog tries not to publish simple summaries. A useful post should add at least one of these:
		evaluation, comparison, practical guidance, workflow design, implementation detail, or a clear point
		of view about where a tool fits.
	</p>
	<p>
		The site separates official claims from interpretation where possible. Product announcements,
		release notes, documentation, repositories, and primary sources are preferred over secondhand
		commentary. When a post relies on a source, the reference should remain visible to readers.
	</p>

	<h2>What the site avoids</h2>
	<p>
		The site avoids low-value SEO pages, copied documentation, unexplained benchmark claims, fake case
		studies, and posts that exist only to chase a keyword. AI tools are useful, but not every launch needs
		an article. If a topic does not have a clear practical angle, it should wait.
	</p>

	<h2>Languages</h2>
	<p>
		FlowHat Blog publishes multilingual posts in English, Korean, and Chinese when appropriate. English
		is usually the canonical draft, and Korean and Chinese versions are derived from it while preserving
		the same argument and source trail. Language-specific pages use matching canonical and hreflang
		metadata so readers and search engines can find the right version.
	</p>

	<h2>Monetization and independence</h2>
	<p>
		FlowHat Blog may use analytics, display advertising, marketplace links, affiliate links, or other
		commercial tools as the publication grows. Monetization should not decide what the site says about a
		tool. Advertising and affiliate details are documented on the <a href="/disclosure/">Disclosure</a>
		page, and data practices are documented on the <a href="/privacy/">Privacy Policy</a> page.
	</p>

	<h2>Updates and corrections</h2>
	<p>
		The AI tooling space changes quickly. Posts may be updated when products change, links move, or new
		context makes the original explanation incomplete. The goal is to keep articles useful, accurate, and
		clear about what is fact, what is a company claim, and what is editorial interpretation.
	</p>

	<h2>Contact</h2>
	<p>
		For corrections, privacy requests, advertising inquiries, or general questions, use the
		<a href="/contact/">Contact</a> page.
	</p>
</PageLayout>
